<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Trustees/Directors of the Muncaster Microbus Ltd (TIC 055)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Trustees/Directors of the Muncaster Microbus Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(TIC 055)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have been operating a small community transport service in rural Cumbria in an area with little or no public transport for 16 years.  We consider that our experie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce is relevant to the inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">about the needs of passengers in isolated rural communities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have commented on each of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">questions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as they were listed in the circulating email</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the Rural Services Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and are willing to give more detail if requ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ired.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban and island communities?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Because the numbers of users are so low, the only effective way of identifying demand is to re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gularly discuss with the local population the service which needs to be provided, ie are there more older people in the population or have several young families </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">moved into the area? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This must include talking to employers, education establishments, busine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sses (eg holiday accommodation providers).  The start or finish of a business or the closing of a service, eg a branch surgery, alters the need for a service.  The service providers also know what the demand in the area is, even if they cannot afford to de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">liver it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (eg people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the vehicles are accessible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the service is flexible, then most peoples’ needs are covered.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In urban areas the vehicles now carry young and old, able-bodied and disabled passenger</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, this should be true in isolated areas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The need to travel is the same – urban transport provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s do not ask why passengers want to travel, so why are the reasons why they want to travel is an issue in the rural areas?  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It appears to be about who should fund the transport.  Funding for transport should be pooled to support transport in rural areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not cost effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to provide money for car schemes to take people to doctors’ surgeries, but not to the hairdresser and for the NHS Patient transport vehicle take people to the local hospital for out patient appointments, but not to visit relatives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in hospital.  There needs to be more joined up thinking.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e the main challenges associated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> with providing better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nd more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities?  How can these challenges be overcome?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to providing transport in an isolated rural area are mainly caused by:-</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">low passengers numbers, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">long distances between passengers, (We have experience of up to 10 miles between pickups)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">distance to where the services are provided (our nearest town is 30 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">miles from the opposite edge of our area),</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quality of the roads which mean that average speeds between pickups can be very slow,</span></li></ul><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most of the challenges can be overcome by flexibility and communitcation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From our experience, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">using </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a smaller vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e-bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oked, dema</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd responsive service allows us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to provide a satisfactory service, which the passengers appreciate.  If the vehicle was any bigger, then the journey times would become unsatisfactorily long.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How effectively do Community Transport services ad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">dress the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From our experience, Community Transport can fairly effectively address the needs of passengers (ie local residents).  However, it is essential that there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">good sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funding and support from the Transport Authority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Community buses should be used for school transport.  A single contract which covers the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisation’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">core costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (eg insurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> road tax, etc.)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will allow the community vehicle to del</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iver service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the rest of the community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at a low cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Services run by residents are sensitive to the changing needs of their community.  Low populations mean that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> critical mass to establish regular bus route</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – flexibility is esse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntial to keep costs at a minimum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in a very dispersed community.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Community transport should not be run centrally by the Transport Authoriy, but should be part of local partnership working, supported by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funding from the Local Authority, NHS and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand responsive services?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Again, local experience in this area shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ost rural residents do not mind booking their travel in advance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> up to the evening before).  Using the demand responsive, pre-booked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> means that the passengers know that the bus will come for them, even if it is delayed.  This preferable to walking a mile along a lane and waiting by the roadside for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the weekly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been cancelled or has just been missed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any rural residents are in low wage jobs, eg agricultural sector, hospitality or are on pensions, and cannot afford the high rates per mile that taxis have to charge.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  It is very difficult for privat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e hire firms to make a living, without working very long hours.  Id</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eally there should be a mix of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> taxi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, group hire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and demand respo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsive bus transport to serve the different needs of the community.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the main challenges associated with funding tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sport services in isolated communities?  How can these services be made more affordable?</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Challenges:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sustainability</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Short term funding</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Confusing transport law and regulations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Partitioning transport into different areas, often funded in different ways eg pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tient transport – NHS funded, school transport – local authority, concessionary fare transport – government/local authority (different budget)</span></li></ul><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ways of helping:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Use community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">groups </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and support volunteers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There may be a need to pay some staff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to run a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reliable and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consistent service.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consistent funding – accept that subsidising transport allows other activities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be sustainable</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mitigate the higher operating costs which apply in rural areas, especially the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">higher cost of fuel and distances to be covered for safety checks.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Encourage patnership working between the organisations that need to move people, eg NHS, Employers, Education suppliers, Social Services, to work together to provide transport that can be u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed for any of these purposes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background of the Organisation:</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The organisation started as a community group and has been operating for 16 years in an area with no bus routes to many of the villages.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Muncaster Microbus Ltd is now a small Limited-by-G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uarantee Company, which is also a Charity, operating in the Copeland Borough of West Cumbria.  It is entirely run by volunteers, operating a single 15 seat, accessible vehicle.  It operates a twice weekly, demand responsive, pre-booked service to Whitehave</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and back to allow personal access to supermarkets, banks, solicitors, opticians, etc.  The vehicle can also be hired by local community groups and is used by the local primary schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Local Geography:</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Microbus operates in 9 rural parishes, which c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 30,279 hectares with a population of 5,519 people.  It is the strip of land which runs between the western side of the Lakeland Mountains and the Irish Sea.  All but one of the parishes are rated super sparse and there are no urban settlements of more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> than 30,000 population within 30 miles.  The roads serving the area are single carriageway, county roads.  The main road through the area was downgraded from being a Trunk road a few years ago.  This has limited the chances of the road being improved in a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ny way.  Most of the residents in the area live in two largish villages.  The rest live in smaller hamlets, often along narrow, single track roads.  Some of the villages and hamlets have access to train stations and the train service has improved in the la</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">st few years.  However, walking and cycle routes to the stations often require using dangerous country lanes with no pavements over distances of more than a mile.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>